                <h5>What to Avoid</h5>
                <p>As far as possible, you should avoid touching the diamond directly. If you’re wearing a diamond ring, remember to hold the band while putting it on or taking it off. This way you don’t have to worry about the grease from your fingers getting transferred to the surface of the diamond. When you’re cleaning your jewellery, you need to be very careful about the mild soap you use. Avoid any kind of body wash or soap that has a moisturiser in it as this will leave a film over your diamonds. You should also avoid using any kind of bleach, household cleaner or even toothpaste on your jewellery. In fact, you should remove your jewellery and store it carefully before handling these cleaners. You should also remove your diamond jewellery when you’re applying moisturiser or sunscreen, washing dishes, or even while you’re using hairspray.</p>
                <h5>Diamond Jewellery and Sanitizer</h5>
                <p>Many of us regularly rub our hands with sanitizer to kill germs and bacteria. If you’re wondering about the effect hand sanitizer has on your lab-grown diamond ring, we have some good news for you. It’s safe for you to use sanitizer on hard stones like diamonds as well as precious metals like silver, titanium, platinum and other plated metals. But, if you are wearing a ring that has a soft stone, such as an opal or pearl, you’d be better off removing it before rubbing sanitizer on your hands.</p>
                <p>Cleaning your jewellery isn’t difficult. A quick soak and brush once a week is enough to keep your lab-grown diamond jewellery shining bright. Just remember to always treat your diamonds with love and care for a bright shimmer that never dulls.</p>
